==Rolling stock==


[[Image:MARCHHP-8.jpg|thumb]] 4913 departing Union Station]]
The Penn Line uses diesel as well as electric locomotives for powering trains. Most electric trains are 5-7 cars long (usually made up of all or mostly Kawasaki bilevels). When the [[AEM-7|AEM-7]]s are used, they are usually used in pairs with 5-7 cars because they are a lot older and weaker then the newer [[HHP-8|HHP-8]]s. However, when there are only 3-5 cars, there will be only one AEM-7.  Rush hour diesel trains are usually 5 cars long (usually made up of all or mostly Kawasaki bilevels). During the day, shorter 3-5 car single level diesel trains from the [[Brunswick_Line|Brunswick]] and [[Camden_Line#Camden_Line|Camden]] lines are used on the Penn Line. All trains are operated in [[Push-pull_train|push-pull]] configuration (with cab-car end towards Union Station). All stations from [[Halethorpe_(MARC_station)|Halethorpe]] to [[Union_Station_(Washington,_D.C.)|Union Station]] have [[Railway_platform_height|high-level platforms]], and all stations from [[Perryville_(MARC_station)|Perryville]] to [[West_Baltimore_(MARC_station)|West Baltimore]], with the exception of Penn Station, have low-level platforms. This precludes the use of MARC's ex-[[Metra|Metra]] low-level boarding gallery cars on the Penn Line.

==Service==
The majority (39) of Penn Line trains run between [[Union_Station_(Washington,_D.C.)|Union Station]] in Washington and [[Baltimore_Penn_Station|Penn Station]] in Baltimore with 12 trains running between Union Station and Perryville and another 5 terminating/originating at Martin State Airport. Unlike MARC's other two lines, the Penn Line operates all day and well into the night with limited weekend service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mta.maryland.gov/sites/default/files/Penn-Weekend-Grid.pdf |format=PDF |title=Penn Line Weekend Schedule |publisher=MTA Maryland |date=September 2013 |accessdate=2013-09-24}}</ref>

Amtrak's [[Acela_Express|Acela Express]], [[Northeast_Regional|Northeast Regional]], and long distance trains share the tracks with the Penn Line and share stations with MARC at [[Aberdeen_(MARC_station)|Aberdeen]], [[Baltimore_Penn_Station|Penn Station]], [[BWI_Rail_Station|BWI Rail Station]], [[New_Carrollton_(Washington_Metro)|New Carrollton]], and [[Union_Station_(Washington,_D.C.)|Union Station]]. Currently, MARC passengers with monthly and weekly tickets can ride most Amtrak Northeast Regional trains on weekends and select Amtrak Northeast Regional trains during the week. Connections are also available to the [[Orange_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Washington Metro Orange Line]] at New Carrollton, [[Red_Line_(Washington_Metro)|Washington Metro Red Line]] at [[Union_Station_(Washington,_D.C.)|Union Station]], and to [[MTA_Light_Rail|MTA Light Rail]] at Baltimore Penn Station.

The MTA has plans to extend the Penn Line to [[Newark_Rail_Station_(Delaware)|Newark, Delaware]] to connect with the [[Wilmington/Newark_Line|Wilmington/Newark Line]] of SEPTA, and to also extend the line past Union Station into northern Virginia.<ref>[http://www.mtamaryland.com/marc%20plan%20full.pdf MARC Growth & Investment Plan] MTA Maryland (September 2007). Retrieved 2010-2-16</ref> The planned [[Purple_Line_(Maryland)|Purple Line]] that will connect all three MARC lines will connect with the Penn Line at New Carrollton.
